{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_horsetail_ver01/data/sn86075141/00340582032/1938012701/0705.xml":{"full_text":"UNION ORGANIZERS\n10 IN\nAOjf\nSCREEN\nR\u00c7 6\u00dcUD\nhEiW\nG\n\nA\n\nAn artist depicts the active work being carried on by the famous\ncomedians, Charlie McCarthy and Edgar Bergen, in building the\n(Federated Pictures)\nScreen Actors Guild.\nJOINT COMMITTEE TO\nMEET FEBRUARY 6TH\n(Continued from Page 1)\nand took no active part in the selec\ntion of candidates for the legisla\nture, except to make endorsements\nof individuals who had already filed\nfor the primaries. As a result about\ntwenty-five candidates received la\nbor endorsements for ten jobs. Many\nof the men endorsed did not deserve\nsuch endorsement as their records\nin the past were w\u00e8ll known.\nThe history of the passage or non\npassage of labor legislation at the\n25th legislative session is too well\nknown to bear repetition. It was a\ncomplete fiasco. The blanket eight\nhour bill with which it was intend\ned to put teeth in the eight-hour\namendment to the Constitution of\nMontana, was defeated by a reac\ntionary senate. The occupational\ndisease (silicosis) bill was also de\nfeated by the- same body. To cap\nthe climax the eight-hour collar-to\ncollar bill which would have affect\ned thousands of miners throughout\nthe sate, was also killed with six of\nthe Silver Bow County representa\ntives voting to kill same, thus ac\nquiring the title of the Servile Six.\nSome of these men had been en\ndorsed by organized labor but they\nfailed on their pre-election pledges\nfor such endorsement.\nBelieving that these conditions\nshould be rectified, Spiegel has de\nvised the following plan; That each\nand every labor union should send\ntwo delegates to a meeting for the\npurpose of organizing a labor legis\nlative committee; that this commit\ntee should pick candidates from the\nranks of labor upon whom they\ncould reasonably rely and request\nthat they support the platform of\nlabor legislation which would be\nadopted by such committee. The\nlabor unions would be requested to\nrefrain from making any other en\ndorsement of candidates for these\nsame offices so that the issues would\nbe clear cut and the workers would\nbe enabled to support the ten men\nchosen without such support being\nsplit as in the past.\nGoing further, Spiegel has con\ntacted every labor organization in\nthe state advocating the adoption of\nthis same plan in their county so\nthat a majority of representatives\nand senators favorable to labor\nwould dominate the next session of\nthe state legislature.\nThe responses favoring such ac\ntion have far exceeded the hopes of\nthe proponent of the plan. Many\nof the larger counties have respond\n:'V\n\n'y\u00ef\n\u2022x;\nm\n\n'i\n\nc\n\ni\nI\nm\nI\n>7^\n\nREGULARLY \u00bb5 to \u00bb6\n'\u00bb55 <A\nk# AND jT\n45\nAll Sizes and Widths But Not in Every Style\nFINAL WEEK OF SALE!\nTHE SYMONS STORE\nMASS MEETING HELD\nTO RELIEVE DISTRESS\n(Continued from Page 1)\nProgress Administration the follow\ning day. They include additional\nmoney from Washington and greater\nrelief, in many instances for the\nsingle persons.\nThe meeting was presided over by\nRobert Brown of the Miners Union.\nIncluded among the other speakers\nwas Mrs. Kerr Beadle, who gave a\nvery frank, enlightening speech on\nthe Townsend issue; Mr. Albert St.\nGeorge, also representing the Town\nsend Club; Elmer Fredrickson of the\nWorkers Alliance; Mr. Metcalf, rep\nresenting the Attorney General's of\nfice, who defended the action of\nAttorney Freebourn in his reluc\ntance to prosecute the persons who\nraided the commodity storehouse in\nGreat Falls, and Clarence Blewett,\nrepresenting the Silver Bow Trades\nand Labor Council.\nMr. Fredrickson of the Workers\nAlliance gave a very clear outline\nof the demands of the people on re\nlief and who are working for the\nWPA as to what they wanted the\ngovernment to do. The audience\nwas assured that the unions and the\nSilver Bow Trades and Labor Coun\ncil were solidly behind the efforts\nof President Roosevelt and also the\nefforts of the working people to gain\nadequate relief and adequate work\nrelief.\nThis U. S. Steel report omits all\nmention of \"profits\" in line with\nthe new \"Eakin formula\" of apple\nsauce accounting.\nUnder this method of fooling the\ncustomers, A. E. Staley Mfg. Co.,\ncorn refiners, turns profits into\nsyrup like \"payments to owners as\nwages or rentals for th\u00ee assets which\nthey have made available to em\nployees.\"\nIf you want to recall things, tie a\nstring around your finger; if you\nwant to forget things, tie a rope\naround your neck.\ned favorably. The response in Sil\nver Bow County has been so great\nthat the calling of a meeting for the\nfurtherance of the plan seems justi\nfied, Consequently all delegates ap\npointed to represent their organiza\ntions at this meeting are requested\nto meet at Musicians hall, 41%\nNorth Main Street, Sunday, Febru\nary 6th, at 2 p. m. Delegates are\nrequested to bring credentials to the\nmeeting at which Mr. Spiegel will\noutline his plan in detail.\nDELEGATES TO TRADES\nCOUNCIL ENJOY SOCIAL\n(Continued From Page 1)\nFrier's character impersonations\nwere unique, comical, and clever.\nThe incongruous expression of some\nof the characters he was personify\ning were ludicrous and caused many\nlaughs.\nThe next delightful part of the\nprogram consisted of Professor Jack\nson of the Musicians Union and Paul\nFrier, Jr., a young man about 6\nyears old, playing a violin duet. Fol\nlowing this, Professor Jackson gave\nimitations on his violin of a singing\ncanary bird, the braying of a don\nkey, the squeaking of a water pump\nand the playing of a church organ.\nNo party would be complete with\nout Frank Heffern and his famous\naccordion. \u00bbFrank can almost make\nthe instrument talk. Another out\nstanding hit of the evening was\nHarvey King and his educated trum\npet. It would be difficult to men\ntion who was best in all of these\nperformances. They were all so\ngood it would be a crime to make\na choice.\nA group of three called the Rocky\nMountain Trio rendered yeoman\nservice. These three consisted of\nGeorge Wetkiff, Carl Wright, and\nHarvey King. A ripple of admira\ntion was noticeable when Miss Fran\nces Logan began her part, singing\na number of popular jazz songs ac\ncompanied by the above mentioned\nRocky Mountain Trio. She was\ngracious and charming. Buddy\nNewton was next on the program in\nsongs accompanied by Carl Wright.\nHe was followed by Dennis Sullivan\nand songs by the Rocky Mountain\nTrio. Both of these men received\nthe applause of the house.\nPalmer from his elevation on the\nrostrum next announced the ap\npointment of Eddie Price as director\nof the next phase of the program\nwhich consisted of songs by the en\ntire house with music furnished by\nmembers of the Musicians Union. If\nthere ever was a gathering that Ed\ndie Price couldn't pep up they've\nlong passed beyond, they are cer\ntainly not of this earth. But it must\nbe admitted that the crowd at the\nSilver Bow Trades and Labor Coun\ncil social certainly were in the mood\nto be exhilarated and it didn't take\nmuch pressure by Eddie to do the\ntrick. Everyone laughed and sang\nand laughed some more, especially\nat Eddie Price's antics and humor\nous remarks. He dedicated one par\nticular song to the Cousin Jacks as\nhe called them, namely, \"My Wild\nIrish Rose,\" and then he dedicated\nthe next song to the Irish, \"Going\nUp Camborne Hill Coming Down.\"\nMayor Charles Hauswirth held a\ndignified position on the officers'\nStand. He was surrounded by\nbottles, whether of his own or of\nthe other celebrities, no one seemed\nto be able to determine. It was\nnoticed though that he had to un\nloosen the top button of his trou\nsers. He was called by Eddie Price\nto sing a song, but instead he gave\nsome outlandish dramatic sketch.\nPalmer said it was one of Shake\nspeare's. However, this was denied\nby the more erudite members of the\nCouncil. The Mayor refused to\ncommit himself as to who wrote the\npiece, but notwithstanding, all these\nconjectures, the characterization was\nput forth, equalled that of the fa\nmous Borus Karloff. They didn't\nthink the Mayor had so much drama\nin his system.\nAs a windup of a perfect night, a\ncrew of male voices made the wel\nkin ring. This group consisted of\nFrank Heffern at the piano and Den\nnis Sullivan acting as leader. The\nchoir composed the following; Hugh\nDoyle, Walter Japp, Joe Cavanaugh,\nSam Spiegel, John (Spotty) John\nson, Maurice Mulcahy, Bill Fauss,\nand Harry Oates. When the party\nbroke up the echoes of \"Sweet Ade\nline\" could still be heard at Park\nand Main Streets.\nBridget Shea did a fine job of\nserving refreshments. Palmer ap\npointed the following to preserve\npeace and order: Chief of Police,\nRosa Schwanekamp of the Librar\nians Unions. Members of her force\nwere William Fauss, Tim Harring\nton, James Comba, and Charles\nRollman. Waiters who were un\nable to show proper union creden\ntials for the Cooks and Waiters but\nplenty of speed were, J. Lunney,\nCharles Davis, A1 DeForest, Walter\nJaap, Henry Oates, Sarah Johnson,\nand Charles Rollman.\nIf the author of this article has\noverlooked any names or any part\nof the program, he wishes to apolo\ngize, as he tried to include everyone;\nwho participated.\nAs an afterthought, however, that\nshould not be overlooked, was Jack\nDriscoll, the dignified officer of the\nFederal Labor Union doing the Big\nApple dance.\nMembers of organized labor who\nmissed this party have something to\nregret for the rest of their natural\nlives.\nCORRECTION IN KGVO\nPROGRAM\nOn Monday, Wednesday, and\nFriday, the schedule reads 2:00\nto 2:30 p. m. \"Reverie Lane and\nSalon Moments,\nread \"This and That\" between\n2:00 and 2:30 p. m.\nIt should\nSHORTER HOURS AND\nWAGE PROTECTION\nURGED BY WM. GREEN\n(Continued from Page 1)\ntend coverage in the payment of un\nemployment benefits and old-age\nbenefits; to provide for payment of\nlarger old-age benefits; to put in\neffect a system of extended bene\nfits for a limited period beyond the\npresent limit of employment benefit\npayments, and, to integrate the ad\nministration of unemployment com\npensation and relief.\n\"(7) Resumption of the work re\nlief program on an extended scale\nduring the immediate period of\nemergency with increased appropri\nation for that purpose.\"\nUnemployment Demands Shorter\nHours\nIn considering the paramount ne\ncessity of shortening the hours of\nwork in industrial employment by\nmaximum hour regulation the A. F.\nof L. president said:\nunemployment situation\npresents a gloomy and discouraging\npicture. It strikes a final and un\nbearably cruel blow at the men and\nwomen who have barely had a\nchance during the brief period of\nincreased economic activity to liqui\ndate the deficits run up in the years\nof the last depression from the in\ncomes secured out of their meager\nearnings. It is an even worse blow\nto those who have not had the op\nportunity of obtaining re-employ\nment provided by our private in\ndustry.\nIncrease of Technological Un\nemployment\n\"Part of the current unemploy\nment is unquestionably due to the\nincreased productivity resulting\nfrom technological changes.\n\"We still hear persistent discus\nsion of bringing industrial activity\nback to 'normalcy' invariably based\non comparisons with the so-called\n'normal' year of 1929.\n\"In considering such statements,\nwe must bear in mind two funda\nmental facts: First, that since 1929\nthe number of wage earners seek\ning employment has increased by\nnearly five million; and, second, that\nthe technological changes and the\nresulting increases in productivity\nhave made it possible to produce the\nsame volume of goods with a con\nsiderably smaller labor force.\n\"During the eight years since the\nbeginning of the last depression, we\nhave failed to apply any remedy\nsufficiently effective to halt the rise\nin unemployment. We have now\naccumulated an additional force of\njob-seekers, some five million in\nstrength, whom industry must ab\nsorb.\nShorter Hours by Legislation Is\nImperative\n\"In dealing with employment in\nthe depression and the possibilities\nof a return to even 1929 conditions,\nProfessor J. M. Clark of Columbia\nUniversity in his notable study made\nthe following significant statement:\n'Improvements have been\nmade since 1929, enabling a giv\nen output to be produced with\nless labor, and many more prob\nably stand ready for introduc\ntion when confidence revives\nsufficiently and when the con\ndition of the capital market\nmakes it possible to raise the\nnecessary funds. Thus, unless\nthere is a shortening of hours in\nindustry there may be a\nconsiderable amount of unem\nployment even after the current\nrevival has gone as far as it\ncan.'\n\"Labor maintains that the short\nening of hours of work in industry\nis an essential prerequisite to the\nreduction of unemployment. Legis\nlative action to make effective this\nshortening of hours should be Item\nNumber One on the agenda of this\nCongress.\"\nWorkers Buying Power Must Be\nProtected\nTurning to the equally important\nquestion of \"continued expansion of\nbuying power\" of the workers \"to\nre-establish recovery,\" Mr. Green\ndeclared:\n\"Our best means of providing re\nemployment and business revival is\nthrough sustaining the purchasing\npower of the vast mass of the Amer\nican wage earners.\n\"Drastic technological changes\nwhich have taken place have result\ned in greater productivity per man\nper hour in all of our major indus\ntries.\n\"New strip mills currently in\nstalled by steel manufacturers call\nfor twenty-five workers in their\noperation where more than one\nhundred had been previously re\nquired.\n\"Labor-saving machinery of simi\nlar kind has been installed and is\nbeing installed in many other man\nufacturing plants.\n\"When this is the case, even with\nthe maintenance of the present wage\nrates, labor costs will be drastically\nreduced.\n\"We cannot permit the workers to\nmake a double contribution to the\nmachine production in the form of\nboth wage cuts and unemployment.\n\"If the volume of production re\nsulting from the installation of new\nmachinery is to be absorbed by the\nconsuming public, the purchasing\npower of the mass of the workers\nmust be sustained. Otherwise these\ntechnological improvements will\nlead us to economic disaster instead\nof economic and industrial progress.\"\n'The\nUnions Ask For More\nGrants For Relief\n(Continued from Page 4)\nwhich would enable them to main\ntain themselves and their families,\nand\nBE IT FURTHER RESOLVED,\nthat the county attorney be urged to\nuse his office to urge the judges of\nthe district court to immediately\nempanel a jury to try the action\ninasmuch as the alleged offense oc\ncurred when the jury was in session\nand was not filed until the regular\njury term was completed, and\nBE IT FURTHER RESOLVED,\nthat we deplore any attempt on the\npart of officials and any employer\nto destroy any effectiveness of un\nion organization by singling out the\nleaders for attack.\nAdopted by.\nJanuary\n1938.\nThe Teamsters are seeking to en\nter into contracts with all the gar\nages and filling stations in Cascade\nCounty, according to report made\nat the last meeting.\nBoilermakers reported that not\nwithstanding the fact that there is\nnow a campaign going on urging\nthe purchase of Montana made gaso\nline and oil, certain Montana oper\nators are installing equipment in the\nMontana field with labor from out\nof the state. A letter was ordered\nsent to J. N. Thelen and also to the\nmen in charge of this campaign\ncalling their attention to this matter\nand asking for an explanation.\nSecretary Whitmore reported that\nthe response toward the establish\nment of a downtown general office\nfor the unions was proceeding nice\nly. Local unions are availing them\nselves of the service of the office at\nthis time. An office manager is in\ncharge daily from 9 a. m. to 1 p. m.\nand 3 p. m. to 5 p. m.\nRaymond Gray, business agent of\nthe Helena Teamsters Union, made\na talk on unionism and the Team\nsters Union in particular.\nThe City Relief Committee of the\nAssembly will meet January 26 at\nthe County Court House. The un\nions are urgently requested to send\ndelegates.\nA Farm-Labor Council organiza\ntion meeting will be held February\n8th at Columbia hall. The unions\nare also expected to send delegates\nto this meeting.\nAt the last meeting of the As\nsembly there were 75 delegates\npresent. It adjourned at 11 p. m.\nThe delegates were then guests of\nthe Eddy Baking Company at a mo\ntion picture called \"White Magic,\"\nand to lunch and other refresh\nments.\nIn connection with the meeting of\nthe Farm-Labor Council at the Co\nlumbia hall, the following letter has\nbeen sent out by Austin G. Thomp\nson to all labor and farm organiza\ntions:\nTo Organized Labor and Organized\nFarmers of Cascade County;\nTo draft a program of county\nwide economic, social and political\ncooperation of workers and farm\ners, representatives of Great Falls\nunions and of Cascade County locals\nof the Montana Farmers Union will\nmeet at Columbia hall, over Ber\nger's store, Tuesday, February 8, at\n8 p. m. (Committeemen who at\ntended preliminary meeting note\nchange in date.)\nYou have been told that coopera\ntion of farmers and organized labor\nis impossible; but Minnesota did it,\nWisconsin did it, North and South\nDakota did it\u2014and two years ago\nHill County, Montana, did it. We\nknow that what these others have\ndone, Cascade County can do\u2014for\nthe benefit of all of us.\nWe want every labor union and\nFarmers Union to have a\nevery\nvoice in the preparation of a pro\ngram which will help all. For this\nreason you are urgently requested\nto send at least one delegate from\nyour organization to the organiza\ntion meeting of the proposed council\nfor joint action.\nColumbia hall, 8 p. m., Tuesday,\nFeb. 8.\nFraternally,\nAustin G. Thompson, Acting\nSecretary, Preliminary Com\nmittee for Farm-Labor Coun\ncil.\nIf we seek happiness for ourselves,\nwe are being selfish in a far-sighted\nsort of way.\nIndependently Owned and Operated\n\u2022Ill\n\u00cf\nTHURSDAY-FRIDAY Jan. 27-28\nGUY KIBBEE in\n\"THE BIG SHOT\n-also\n\"KING OF HOCKEY\"\nWith DICK PURCELL\nJan. 29\nSATURDAY\n\"CHEROKEE STRIP'\nWith DICK FORA*,\nThe Singing Cowboy\nJan. 30-31\nSUND AY-MONDAY\nTHE RITZ BROTHERS\n'LIFE BEGINS IN\nCOLLEGE\"\nLEGAL NOTICES\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nEsatte of ANNA TOMICH, Deceased.\nNotice is hereby given by the under\nsigned, Administratrix of the estate of\nAnna Tomich, deceased, to the creditors\nof and all persons having claims against\nthe said deceased, to exhibit them, with\nnecessary\nmonths after the first publication of this\nnotice to the said administratrix at the\noffice of Harlow Pease. 409 Silver Bow\nBlk., Butte, Mont., the same being the\nplace for the transaction of the business\nof said estate, i\nBow. State of Montana.\nANGELA M. STONE, Administra\ntrix of the Estate of Anna Tomich,\nDeceased.\nDated Butte, Montana, this 18th day of\nJanuary, 1938.\nFirst publication January 20, 1938.\u20144T.\nvouchers,\n\nthe County of Silver\nCERTIFICATE OF INDIVIDUAL TRAN\nSACTING BUSINESS WITHIN THE\nSTATE OF MONTANA UNDER A FIC\nTITIOUS NAME.\nI, the undersigned, hereby and hereon\ncertify as follows:\nThat I am an individual now transact\ning business, and who will hereafter tran\nsact business in the State of Montana\nunder a fictitious name and style, to-wit:\n\"MODERN GROCERY CONFECTION\nERY CO.''; that the county wherein the\nprincipal iilace of business of said busi\nness is situated\nin the County of Silver\nBow, in the State of Montana; that my\nname in full Is: DESPINA FAMOS, re\nsiding at 505 Illinois Avenue, City of\nButte, County of Silver Bow, Montana;\nThat said business known as \"MOD\nERN GROCERY CONFECTIONERY\nCO.\" is being conducted at 336 South\nMontana Street. City of Butte. County of\nSilver Bow. State of Montana.\nDated this 19th day of January, A. D.\n1938.\nDES BIN A FAMOS.\nState of Montana, County of Silver\nBow, ss:\nOn this 19th day of January, A. D. 1938,\nbefore me, G. V. Brew, a Notary Public\nfor the State of Montana, personally ap\npeared DESPINA FAMOS, known to me\nto be the person described in, and whose\nname is subscribed to the foregoing cer\ntificate, and acknowledged to me that she\nexecuted the same.\nIN WITNESS WHEREOF. I have here\nunto set my hand and affixed my official\nthe day and year in this certlfi\nseal\ncate first above written.\nG. V. BREW. Notary Public for the\nState of Montana, Residing at\nButte, Montana. My commission\nexpires Oct. 8, 1940.\n(NOTARIAL SEAL)\nFirst publication January 20, 1938.\u20144T.\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nEstate of CECIL R. SULLIVAN. Deceased.\nNotice is hereby given by\nsigned, administratrix of the\nCecil R. Sullivan, deceased, to the credi\ntors of and all persons having claims\nagainst the said deceased, to exhibit them,\nwith the necessary vouchers, within four\nmonths after the first publication of this\nnotice to the said administratrix at Coun\nty Attorney's Office, c|o H. F. O'Connell,\nButte, Montana, the same being the place\nfor the transaction of the business of said\nestate, in the County of Silver Bow, State\nof Montana.\nthe under\nestate of\nCAROLYN L. SULLIVAN, Adminis\ntratrix ol the Estate of Cecil R.\nSullivan, Deceased.\nDated Butte, Montana, this 20th day of\nJanuary, 1938.\nFirst publication January 27, 1938.\u2014-IT,\nNo. 37196\nALIAS SUMMONS\nIn the District Court of the Second Ju\ndicial District of the State of Montana,\nIn and for the County of Silver Bow.\nPETER TROGLIA, Plaintiff,\nANNA S. TROGLIA, Defendant.\nThe State of Montana Sends Greetings\nto the Above Named Defendant:\nhereby summoned to answer\nthis action, which is filed\nYou\nthe complaint in\nin the office of the Clerk of this Court, a\ncopy of which is herewith served upon\nyou, and to file your answer and serve a\ncopy thereof upon the plaintiff's attorney\nwithin twenty days after the service of\nthis summons, exclusive of the day of\nservice: and in\nappear or answer, judgment\nagainst you by default for the relief de\nmanded in the complaint, to-wit; wherein\nit is alleged that the plaintiff and de\nfendant intermarried at Butte, in the\nCounty of Silver Bow, State of Montana,\nabout the 28th day of June, 1936,\nand ever since have been, and are now,\nhusband and wife. That the plaintiff has\nbeen a resident of the State of Montana\nfor more than one year immediately pre\nceding the commencement of this action.\nThat during\nriage a child\nAnna S. Troglia, on August 25, 1937, at\nPocatello, Idaho, which child was named\ncy Theophll Troglia. That on or about\n26th day of August, 1936, the defend\nant, disregarding the solemnity of her\nmarriage vows, and with intent to desert,\nwillfully and without cause, deserted and\nabandoned this plaintiff; and has ever\nsince, and does still continue to, willfully\nand without cause desert and abandon\nthis plaintiff and to live separate and\napart from him, without sufficient cause\nor reason and against his will and without\nhis consent. That\nabandonment within mentioned continued\nup to the time of the commencement of\nthis action.\nof your failure to\nwill be taken\nHi\nthe existence of said mar\nwas born to the defendant,\nPer\nHu\nsaid desertion and\nWHEREFORE plaintiff prays that the\nbonds of matrimony heretofore and now\nexisting between the plaintiff and the de\nfendant be dissolved, and that the plain\ntiff be granted an absolute divorce from\nthe defendant; and for such other and\nfurther relief as to the Court may seem\njust and equitable in the premises.\nWITNESS my hand and the seal of said\nCourt, this.day of January, A. D. 1938.\nELMER SHEA, Clerk.\n(COURT SEAL)\nJOE C. GIACOMA,\nAttorney for Plaintiff.\nFirst publication January 27, 1938.\u20144T.\nNo. 10850\nNOTICE OF TIME APPOINTED FOR\nPROVING WILL AND HEARING\nAPPLICATION FOR LETTERS\nTESTAMENTARY\nIn the District Court of the Second Ju\ndicial District of the State of Montana,\nIn and for the County of Silver Bow.\nIn the Matter of the Estate of JOHN\nOLSON. Deceased.\nPursuant to\ntitled Court duly given and made herein\non the 26th day of January, 1938, NOTICE\nIS HEREBY GIVEN that Friday, the 11th\nday of February, 1938, at 9:30 o'clock A.\nM. of said day. before the above entitled\nCourt, at the court room of said Court, in\nDepartment No. One, thereof, at the Court\nHouse In the City of Butte, in the County\norder of the above en\n'8\nSAFEWAY NEVER KNOWINGLY\nUNDERSOLD AT ANYTIME!\nYou'll Like Its Rich, Full-Bodied Flavor\u2014\nWe Know You'll Like Its Price\n19c\nPound Can\nNavel Oranges\n(U. S. No. 1) Your Choice of Size\n$1.29\nx h (rale\nWashington Cooperative Eggs\nMedium Extras, Dozen\nLarge Specials, Dozen\n23c\n27c\nAirway Coffee\nMild and Mellow Flavor\n15c\nPound Bag\nof Silver Bow. State of Montana, have\nbeen appointed as the time and place for\nproving the last will and testament of said\nJohn Olson, deceased, and for hearing the\napplication and petition ot Martha Olson\nfor the issuance to her of Letters Testa\nmentary thereon,\nperson interested may appear and con\ntest said last will and testament of said\ndeceased and may file objections in writ\ning to the granting of Letters Testa\nmentary\nDated\n'hen and where any\npetitioner,\nry 26th, 1938.\nSHEA, Clerk of the above\nto said\nJanuar\nELMER\nentitled Court.\nBy F. J. GABSE. Deputy Clerk.\n(COURT SEAL\u00bb\nFirst publication January 27. 1938.\u20144T.\nSHERIFF S SALE UNDER ORDER\nOF SALE\nHOME OWNERS LOAN CORPORATION,\na Corporation, Plaintiff,\n\nW. S BYRAM, AGNES BYRAM. JOHN\nHATHERELL and AVIS 1IATHERELL,\nDefendants.\nTO BE SOLD AT SHERIFF'S SALE on\nthe 18th day of February. A. D. 1938, at\n2:00 o'c ock P. M., at the front door of\nthe County Court House, City of Butte,\nCounty of Silver Bow. State of Montana,\nthe following described real property, to\nwit:\nAll of Lot Numbered Twenty-four\n(24) and the East Half of Lot Twenty\nthree (23) in Block Sixteen (16) of tne\nBellevue Addition to the City of Butte.\nCounty of Silver Bow. State of Mon\ntana. according to the plat thereof\non file and of record in the of\nfice of the Clerk and Recorder In and\nfor the County of Silver Bow. State of\nMontana.\nLAWRENCE WEIR. Sheriff Silver\nBow County. Montana.\nBy WILLIAM HOLLAND. Deputy\nSheriff.\nDated January 26. A. D. 1938.\nFirst publication January 27, 1938 \u20144T.\nNOTICE TO CREDITORS\nEstate of WINNIFRED DARRAGH. De\nceased.\nNotice is hereby given by\nsigned, administrator of th\nthe under\ne estate of\nWinnifred Darragh, deceased, to the credi\ntors of and all persons having claims\nagainst the said deceased, to exhibit them,\nwith the necessary vouchers, within four\nmonths after the first publication of this\nnotice to the said administrator at room\n42 in the Hirbour Building, Butte, Mon\ntana, the same being the place for the\ntransaction of the business of said estate,\nin the County of Silver Bow, State of\nMontana.\nJOSEPH DARRAGH, Administrator\nof the Estate of Winnifred Dar\nragh, Deceased.\nDated Butte, Montana, this 24th day of\nJanuary, 1938.\nW. B. FREEBOURN,\nAttorney for the Administrator.\nFirst publication January 27, 1938.\u20144T.\nUnion Members Patronize Labor\nNews Advertisers\nYOUTH FOR WORK\nAGE FOR LEISURE\"\nJOIN BUTTE TOWNSEND\nCLUB No. 1\nMeets Every Friday Evening\nat Y. M, C. A.\nFinal Wind-Up\nof MURRAY'S\nClean Sweep\nUsed Car\nBargains\nWhy Walk?\n'28 Marraon Sedan\n'29 Hudson Sport Coupe\n'30 Essex DeLuxe Sedan\n'29 Chevrolet Coach\n'29 Nash \"6\" Sedan\n'29 Pontiac Sedan\n'29 Dodge \"6\" Sedan.\n'29 Ford Coach\n*29 Chevrolet Coupe\n'29 Reo Sedan\n'30 Dodge Sedan\n'29 Chevrolet Sport Coupe\n'30 Ford Coach\n25\n30\n35\n45\n50\n55\n60\n65\n70\n7